The DA says it has a plan to de-regulate the price of fuel. The party says the law must be amended to curtail the minister’s powers to regulate the price of fuel. eNCA's Lindsay Dentlinger reports. #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - Cape Town residents are fed up, despite reprieves in the severity of blackouts compared to the rest of the country. The price of electricity has gone up 9.5 percent this month for city customers. READ: DA unveils bill to cut fuel price And now the fuel price hike is expected to add to food and transport costs. But the DA says it has a plan to de-regulate the price of fuel. The party says the law must be amended to curtail the minister’s powers to regulate the price of fuel. WATCH: Fuel hike shocker for July It says petrol should cost no more than R19 a litre. The party will introduce its bill to amend the law to Parliament soon. * eNCA's Lindsay Dentlinger reports.